Critics gave ''Where in the USA Is Carmen Sandiego?'' positive reviews, although many reviews negatively compared it with its predecessor. The smaller scope of ''Where in the U.S.A....'' may have reduced its relevance for potential players who lived outside the United States.

In 1987, ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' complimented the game as a valuable tool for teaching geography, reference book use, map reading, and deductive reasoning.<ref name="proctor198707">{{cite news | title=Educational Games From Broderbund | magazine=Computer Gaming World | date=June–July 1987 | last=Proctor |first=Bob | page=26}}</ref> ''[[Compute!'s Gazette|Compute! Gazette]]'' said the "educational and challenging" work was "so intriguing that players will be drawn to it again and again, learning a little more about logic, common sense, and U.S. geography each time".<ref name="CarmenUSA1986-CGazette"/> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} [[Thomas L. Friedman]] described the game as "a wonderful geography-teaching tool".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/16/opinion/foreign-affairs-where-do-cars-come-from.html | title=WASH Foreign Affairs; Where Do Cars Come From? | work=The New York Times | date=April 16, 1995 | access-date=November 18, 2012 | author=Friedman, Thomas L. | archive-date=November 14, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114084036/http://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/16/opinion/foreign-affairs-where-do-cars-come-from.html | url-status=live }}</ref> Gregg Keizer of ''[[Compute!]]'' said the game is "redeeming" when compared with the "sociopathic" ''Task Force'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue126/M8_Give_your_Apple_II_a.php|title=Give your Apple II a New Year's treat|last=Keizer|first=Gregg|website=www.atarimagazines.com|access-date=April 19, 2017|archive-date=April 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420143730/http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue126/M8_Give_your_Apple_II_a.php|url-status=live}}</ref> while ''[[Compute!]]'s'' Warren Buckleitner called it an "outstanding" and "excellent" example of edutainment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue136/S10_25_top_childrens_pr.php|title=25 top children's programs|last=Buckleitner|first=Warren|website=www.atarimagazines.com|access-date=April 19, 2017|archive-date=December 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171220173327/https://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue136/S10_25_top_childrens_pr.php|url-status=live}}</ref> Judith Kilbury-Cobb of ''Info 30'' gave the game a rating of 4.5 stars, writing that it is so "engrossing" players would not realize they were learning.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kilbury-Cobb|first=Judith|title=Where in the U.S.A is Carmen Sandiego?|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_7070|journal=Info 30|volume=Jan – Feb 1990|access-date=April 23, 2017|archive-date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424003538/http://amr.abime.net/review_7070|url-status=live}}</ref>

''[[Macworld]]'' reviewed the Macintosh version of ''Where in the USA Is Carmen Sandiego?'', calling it a "lively and challenging way to practice map-reading skills ... Once again Broderbund has produced a learning tool that is not only educational but also loads of fun". ''Macworld'' criticized the key-disk copy protection, which requires one of the game disks to be inserted even if the game is installed.<ref>{{cite magazine|last = Lukos|first = Gerry|title = Atlas Explorer 1.0, Where in the USA Is Carmen Sandiego? 1.0, Global Trespass 1.0 Review|date = November 1989|url = https://archive.org/details/MacWorld_8911_November_1989|magazine = Macworld|publisher = Mac Publishing|page = [https://archive.org/details/MacWorld_8911_November_1989/page/n236 217]–220}}</ref>

Phil Campbell of ''Australian Commodore and Amiga Review'' described aspects of the game as "fun", "delightful", and "effective", while calling the game a worthy sequel to ''Where in the World Is Carmen Sandiego?''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=Phil|date=February 1990|title=Where in the USA Is Carmen Sandiego?|url=https://archive.org/stream/Australian_Commodore_and_Amiga_Review_The_Volume_7_Issue_2_1990-02_Saturday_Magazine_AU#page/n65/mode/2up/search/carmen+sandiego|journal=Australian Commodore and Amiga Review|volume=7|issue=2|pages=66}}</ref> ''The House of Games'' gave the title a score of 7/10, writing that it plays the same as its predecessor, questioning its appeal to those outside of the United States, and giving it a lower score than ''World'' for this reason.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thehouseofgames.org/index.php?t=10&id=343|title=Where in the USA is Carmen Sandiego|last=Kaiser|first=Erde|date=2017|website=The House of Games|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424034325/http://thehouseofgames.org/index.php?t=10&id=343|archive-date=2016-04-24|url-status=dead|access-date=April 23, 2017}}</ref> ''The Journal News'' said the game is one of the more popular spin-offs from ''[[Where in the World Is Carmen Sandiego? (1985 video game)|Where in the World Is Carmen Sandiego?]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/162777037/|title=That's 'edu-tainment'|last=DeBarros|first=Anthony|date=June 16, 1992|work=The Journal News|access-date=April 23, 2017|pages=19|language=en|archive-date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424005821/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/162777037/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Arizona Republic'' said the CD-ROM version of the game is a "sure winner".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/117161862/|title=Arizona Republic from Phoenix, Arizona on December 4, 1994 &middot; Page 183|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=April 23, 2017|language=en|archive-date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424013549/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/117161862/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' wrote that the game is "along the same lines of play" as ''World''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/202017530/|title=Chicago Tribune from Chicago, Illinois on December 19, 1986 &middot; Page 203|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=April 23, 2017|language=en|archive-date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424010555/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/202017530/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Jean Donham van Deusen, co-author of ''Teaching With Computers: A New Menu for the Nineties'', ranked the program highly, praised its ability to foster social interaction between players, and wrote that the game overcomes a misconception about computer playing being a solitary activity and that with ''Where in the USA Is Carmen Sandiego?'', the player is in charge of the experience.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/152582085/|title=Reno Gazette-Journal from Reno, Nevada on December 6, 1991 &middot; Page 55|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=April 23, 2017|language=en|archive-date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424010336/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/152582085/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' wrote that the game offers a fun way for players to learn about United States geography.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/141486763/|title=St. Louis Post-Dispatch from St. Louis, Missouri on October 27, 1991 &middot; Page 625|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=April 23, 2017|language=en|archive-date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424013533/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/141486763/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Tennessean]]'' said the game's appeal was age-based and that it was unlikely that children who were ten or younger would enjoy the game's challenges.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112837634/|title=The Tennessean from Nashville, Tennessee on November 8, 1995 &middot; Page 23|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=April 23, 2017|language=en|archive-date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424002923/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112837634/|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Tar Heel]]'' noted the game's importance in "a society where most pupils can't identify their home state on a map".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/67863340/|title=The Daily Tar Heel from Chapel Hill, North Carolina on January 30, 1992 &middot; Page 15|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=April 23, 2017|language=en|archive-date=April 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424011628/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/67863340/|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Commercial performance ===
''Where in the U.S.A. Is Carmen Sandiego?'' was the fifth (August 20 through September 16, 1989)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue115/426_1_HOTWARE_SOFTWARE_BESTSELLERS_FROM_AROUND_THE_COUNTRY.php|title=Hotware: Software Bestsellers From Around The Country|last=Country|first=Software Bestellers From Around the|website=www.atarimagazines.com|access-date=April 19, 2017|archive-date=April 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420143230/http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue115/426_1_HOTWARE_SOFTWARE_BESTSELLERS_FROM_AROUND_THE_COUNTRY.php|url-status=live}}</ref> and fourth (June 24 through July 21, 1990)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue123/HOTWARE.php|title=Hotware: Software Best-Sellers|website=www.atarimagazines.com|access-date=April 19, 2017|archive-date=April 20, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420143228/http://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue123/HOTWARE.php|url-status=live}}</ref> best-selling home-learning software according to a ''COMPUTEI's'' Hotware list conducted by Egghead Discount Software. The list was on retail sales of Apple II, Macintosh, and IBM software from Egghead stores in the United States and Canada.

